The United States hosted the International Engagement Conference for South Sudan to welcome the new country to the international community and discuss development priorities. The conference demonstrated the commitment of the United States and the international community to South Sudan. The United States government, along with co-sponsors, pledged to support South Sudan in promoting sound management of national resources, creating a climate for investment and trade, strengthening education, health, and agriculture sectors, and encouraging the participation of women and youth. The Department of Treasury issued general licenses to stimulate investment in South Sudan, and the U.S. Office of the Trade Representative launched a review of South Sudan's eligibility for trade benefits. The Overseas Private Investment Corporation initiated the process to open for business in South Sudan, and USAID focused on agricultural development and healthcare systems in the country. The U.S. government also aimed to support the participation of women in political, social, and economic spheres. Co-sponsors such as Norway, the United Kingdom, Turkey, the United Nations, the World Bank, the International Finance Corporation, the European Union, the African Union, and the Corporate Council on Africa made commitments to support South Sudan's development in various areas.